			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The cast time on the dmg shields seems trvial to me. Reducing the cast time doesn't really matter to me nor does 10 mana reducements. I think that slot could be better used describing something else. What I think most people want is for it to be a buff that will remain in a tank's lineup list. Maybe it's time to add something else to the dmg shield to achieve that or further increase the dmg. The next issue is the one I've thought alot about "I've had 4 years"
<br />

<br />
The fire pet, . From the proposed things that have been put out there it's just going to have the pet remain a "dumb" NPC from what i've seen. That's the problem with him right now. What they need to do is program some smartness into the fire pet and not act like other caster npc's and more like Pc's. 
<br />

<br />
The way I personnaly think it should be done is. First the pet needs an unlimited mana pool, this won't be overpowering though as I explain how later on. Then it should "root" itself and <span style="font-weight: bold">not</span> melee, and <span style="font-weight: bold">not</span> root,debuff,  or aoe. The pet find's out the mob's health that it's nuking. Then begins casting nukes until it hit's a DPS ceiling. This ceiling of course would get higher the better focus you get, and would be comparable to a water pet's normal DPS output for that focus level.  The way he figures out this ceiling is comparing the <span style="font-style: italic">potentional</span> spell damage to the mob's health until it hit's that dps ceiling.  Once it hit's that ceiling it shuts off, unless the mob heal's itself then he begins casting again until he hits the ceiling again. 
<br />

<br />
This potentional spell damage ceiling makes sense to me in a balance sense. The pet can therefore not always land his nukes for full, be interupted, or some other happenstance that  doesn't allow him to land a spell. But the pet will hopefully be near the higher end of the dps charts for pets near the water pet.  This put's the pet in a position of acting like a normal caster who needs to conserve his mana. But since NPC's arn't as smart and don't sit and do normal things that we do plus attain gear to help us out in that department it's done in another way but still garner the same results, him acting like a caster would. We all have a ceiling based on our mana pools, the pet's would be based on your focus and the mob's health.
<br />

<br />
That's just my spin on it, but I truely think if we're to have a caster pet that works they need to act more like humans and not computers. This seems to me to be the simplest way while also addressing balance issues.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Azmeka Raidner on Fri Jul 23, 2004 11:09 pm; edited 5 times in total</span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
